 factors","Phagocytosis of pathogens and debris from portal blood"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EKupffer cells are specialised macrophages located within the hepatic sinusoids. Their primary function is \u003Cstrong\u003Ephagocytosis of pathogens and debris from portal blood\u003C/strong\u003E, helping to filter and clean the blood entering from the gut via the portal circulation. They are part of the reticuloendothelial system and play a crucial role in immune surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options describe different liver cell functions: \u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of bile acids\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Estorage of vitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Esynthesis of clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Etransport of lipids\u003C/strong\u003E are all functions of hepatocytes, not Kupffer cells.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Kupffer cells are specialised macrophages in the liver that phagocytose pathogens and cellular debris from portal circulation.","Kupffer cells are located within hepatic sinusoids and form part of the reticuloendothelial system."],"references":["Dixon LJ, Barnes M, Tang H, Pritchard MT, Nagy LE. Kupffer cells in the liver. Compr Physiol. 2013 Apr;3(2):785-97. doi: 10.1002/cphy.c120026. PMID: 23720329; PMCID: PMC4748178.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52590"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"q